<HEADLINE>
Moral Philosophy &amp; Traffic Engineering
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<POST>
<POSTER> Publius &lt;m.publ...@nospam.comcast.net&gt; </POSTER>
<POSTDATE> 2007-03-08T22:52:00 </POSTDATE>
Moral philosophy, rightly considered, is closely analogous to traffic
engineering. Its aim is to devise a system of rules for governing human
interactions in social settings, just as the task of the traffic engineer is
to devise a system of rules governing the use of public roadways.

The moral philosopher assumes that the setting includes a number of agents,
that there is associated with each of those agents an ordered set of values,
or interests, which that agent seeks to satisfy, and that his actions are
always directed to satisfying one or more of those interests. Which interest
an agent acts to satisfy on a given occasion is determined by the current
weight of that value in the hierarchy and various "external" factors, such as
current opportunities presented by the environment and the current costs to
satisfy them.

Similarly, the traffic engineer assumes that the highway system is used by a
number of drivers, each of whom has a number of destinations to which he may
desire to travel at one time or another (an *itinerary*). The particular
destination chosen by a particular driver at a particular time is a function
of his needs at the moment, opportunities, and costs, just as for the moral
agent. Where the moral philospher is concerned with *acts* undertaken by
agents in a public setting, the traffic engineer is concerned with *trips*
undertaken by drivers on the public road system.

Note that, although I said that agents are "always" pursuing some interest,
(and might also have said that drivers are "always" traveling to some
destination), that neither the moral philosopher nor the traffic engineer
necessarily assumes that agents or drivers do nothing else in their lives.
But any other activities in which they may engage are outside the scope of
the philosopher's or engineer's concern.

Just as the traffic engineer is not concerned with the destinations chosen by
drivers, or their reasons for choosing them on any given occasion, neither is
the moral philosopher concerned with the values or interests pursued by moral
agents, or their reasons for pursuing them (there is an exception to this
rule, however, which we'll consider momentarily).

The traffic engineer, like the moral philosopher, also assumes that drivers
are *autonomous* and *independent*. That is, that the itineraries of drivers,
like the value hierarchies of agents, are chosen by each driver and agent
without regard to the itineraries or hierarchies of other drivers, and that
both agents and drivers are ignorant, for the most part, of others'
itineraries or hierarchies. I say "for the most part" because agents may at
times cooperate in pursuit of some shared interest, and drivers may at times
coordinate their trips, e.g., caravan. But most drivers using the system at
any given time will have no information regarding the destinations of other
drivers and will have no interest in them. Furthermore, the itineraries of
drivers will always differ from those of other drivers in some respect, and
usually in many respects. Likewise with moral agents and their values.

The traffic engineer assumes that without some controls in place for using
the public road system drivers will collide and interfere in other ways with
one another's trips. The moral philosopher assumes, similarly, that without
some rules in place, agents will interfere destructively with one another's
pursuit of their interests. So each adopts a "fundamental principle":

FP (Traffic Engineer): Devise a system of rules which allow all drivers to
complete their trips (reach their destinations) in the shortest possible
time, with the fewest collisions possible.

FP (Moral philosopher): Devise a system of rules which allow all agents to
attain their goals at the least possible cost, with the fewest collisions
possible.

Both also assume a sub-principle of "safety first" --- avoiding collisions
outweighs minimizing travel times or costs.

I mentioned that there was an exception to the generalization that traffic
engineers and moral philosophers are unconcerned with drivers' or agents'
destinations or interests, respectively. The exceptions are those
destinations or interests which are incompatible, *prima facie*, with the
premise of a public road system accessible to all drivers, or with a moral
field open to all agents. Those would include destinations on the public
highway system itself --- one may not end one's trip in the middle of a
roadway. Similarly, one may not, in a social setting, pursue interests which
necessarily preclude others' pursuits of theirs. Only "non-interfering
interests" and "non-interfering destinations" are allowable.

Thus both the traffic engineer and the moral philosopher face an optimization
problem --- to find that set of rules which *best* satisfies their respective
Fundamental Principles.
