I've lurked in some of your Kant threads in ap, apo and apk.
A lot of disagreement, IMO, stems from varying takes on what morality is and
should be.
Schopenhauer torpedoed the CI very early, saying that what Kant is doing is
not describing
morality qua some sort of "goodness", but solely as proper behaviour for a
subject of the Law;
which, of course, is obedience to the law. This is founded on a rational
theory of justice, which in turn rests on freedom, which in turn rests on an
individualism that says that no one knows what is good for everyone - we are
free to engage in the pursuit of our individual happiness, within the
boundaries of fairness (my freedom is limited by that of any others).

Which has little to do with "goodness" in an e.g. religious (faith, hope and
charity) sense, a Nietzschean sense, an Aristotelian sense (virtue ethics)
etc. etc. which all presume some sort of universal goodness one should
attain, or, in the case of Nietzscheans, embody.

To me, this goodness/fairness distinction explains why we have the
inclination/duty brouhaha wrt. Kant.
It is eminently sensible to question his take that morality = obedience to
the law; otoh, rejecting this opens up to all sorts of paternalism, someone
knowing what is good for me without really consulting me, except with
torches and pitchforks should I stray from the straight and narrow.

In a sense he highlights a possible hypothesis that "love" and "freedom" are
antithetical; while we, thx to Jesus &amp; Cie,  are wont to equating "love"
with "goodness" and "goodness" with "being a nice person" and "being a nice
person" with "morality".

