I'd say that Schopenhauer has it completely wrong here.  There are
moralities that are solely concerned with actions or conscious
behavior - consequentialist theories, like my own - but Kant's is not
one of them.  Kant is concerned not just with what rules a moral agent
follows, but more importantly with the 'goodness' of the agent's
will.  IN the examples I quoted, he specifically says that, of two
moral agents who act in exactly the same way, only one - the one who
performs the act purely "from duty" - is acting morally, while the
other - who performs the exact same act from "selfishness" or
"pleasure" - is not being morally good at all.
