&gt; what is clearly a  (consequentialist  (teleoogical) public morality
&gt; onto a deontological (Kantian) ethical foundation.  Why do you prefer
&gt; that particular ethic?

&gt; I can understand your reasons for rejecting utilitarianism, but that's
&gt; not the only consequentialist ethic on the market.   What's your
&gt; reason for rejecting teleology in general?
">

I don't reject teleology in general. Teleology constitutes the substrate, the
precondition, for deontology. We need rules because people have goals, and to
reach those goals they must be free to act, i.e., to choose the methods and
means of attaining them. But in a social setting, they will be tempted to
view others as means to their own ends. And in the absence of some rules,
arrived at via reason, they will have *no reason not to do so*.

Reason tells us that such a strategy, if universally or even widely followed,
is destructive to our own ends, and everyone else's. Hence we direct our
attention to forging some rules.

Moral theory is concerned with those rules, not with the goals sought. Goals
differ among agents, and are not products of reason. Moral rules thus cannot
be rationally justified on the basis of the ends attained when applying them
in particular cases, and certainly not selected because they are productive
of certain ends. They must be justified, instead, on the ground that they
allow all agents maximal freedom to pursue their ends, whatever they may be.
That requires that they be universalizable and regard all agents as ends in
themselves, and not as means to particular ends.

Kant does not dismiss teleology. He only argues that ends cannot be invoked
to justify moral rules. Ends "factor out" in arguments for rules.

However (as we've discussed previously) those rules, once rationally
justified, can become "internalized" by agents and thus become a kind of end,
or good, in their own right --- what we might call "metagoods." That
transformation of rationally justifed rules into metagoods constitutes
progress toward the *summum bonnum*, where virtue and happiness become
coextensive.
